{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9638ca8f-7af8-4d17-88b5-d3d00dcc4b92","content":"The environment has `dotnet` but not `dotnet-dump`. Here's what I recommend:\n\n### To analyze your dump, install `dotnet-dump`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n```\n\nThen open your dump with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-dump analyze <your-file>.dmp\n```\n\n### Key commands once inside the analyzer:\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---------|---------|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `pe` (or `printexception`) | Print the last exception |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch to a specific thread |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for memory issues) |\n\n### Typical crash investigation flow:\n1. **`pe`** — check if there's an unhandled exception\n2. **`clrthreads`** — find threads with exceptions (look for the `Exception` column)\n3. **`setthread <id>`** + **`clrstack`** — inspect the faulting thread's call stack\n4. **`pe -nested`** — see inner exceptions\n\nWould you like me to install `dotnet-dump` and start analyzing your dump file? If so, please share the path to your `.dmp` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"30055804-df6b-4777-ad75-8943472e5fb0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The environment has `dotnet` but not `dotnet-dump`. I could install it. Let me also check if lldb is available.","outputTokens":372},"id":"a0d6c1e2-2a8e-45c0-822c-f1039965978a","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:05:57.806Z","parentId":"73851463-05de-4ea3-8250-18baec81272f"}
